# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: billie-jean-king-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1963-federation-cup-tennis] The **1963 Federation Cup** was the first edition of what is now known as the Fed Cup.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1963-federation-cup-tennis] The tournament was created provide a team competition for women, similar to the Davis Cup men's competition.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1963-federation-cup-tennis] 16 nations participated in the first event, which was held at the Queen's Club in London, United Kingdom from 17–20 June.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1963-federation-cup-tennis] United States won the first title, defeating Australia in the final.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1963-federation-cup-tennis] All ties were played at the Queen's Club in London, United Kingdom on grass courts.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1964-federation-cup-tennis] The **1964 Federation Cup** was the second edition of what is now known as the Fed Cup.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1964-federation-cup-tennis] 20 nations participated in the tournament, which was held at the Germantown Cricket Club in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, United States, from 1–5 September.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1964-federation-cup-tennis] Australia won the title, defeating defending champions United States in the final.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1964-federation-cup-tennis] All ties were played at the Germantown Cricket Club in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, United States on grass courts.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1965-federation-cup-tennis] The **1965 Federation Cup** was a team tennis tournament that took place at the Kooyong Lawn Tennis Club in Melbourne, Australia.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1965-federation-cup-tennis] It was third edition of what is now known as the Fed Cup and had eleven nations participating in the tournament throughout the four days from 15–18 January 1965.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1965-federation-cup-tennis] The eleven teams played in a knockout format with six teams having to play in the opening round to join the remaining five who received first rounds byes.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1965-federation-cup-tennis] After winning all of the ties 3-0, the final was between the United States and Australia who for the third time in consecutive years met up in the final which was played on the 18 January.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1965-federation-cup-tennis] After Lesley Turner and Margaret Smith each recorded wins in the singles, Australia would defend their title that they won in 1964 despite a loss in the doubles.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1965-federation-cup-tennis] All ties were played at the Kooyong Lawn Tennis Club in Melbourne, Australia on grass courts.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1966-federation-cup-tennis] The **1966 Federation Cup** was the fourth edition of what is now known as the Billie Jean King Cup.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1966-federation-cup-tennis] 21 nations participated in the tournament, which was held at the Turin Press Sporting Club in Turin, Italy from 10 to 15 May.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1966-federation-cup-tennis] United States won their second title, defeating West Germany in the final, in what was the first final not featuring Australia.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1966-federation-cup-tennis] All ties were played at the Turin Press Sporting Club in Turin, Italy on clay courts.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1967-federation-cup-tennis] The **1967 Federation Cup** was the fifth edition of what is now known as the Billie Jean King Cup.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1967-federation-cup-tennis] 17 nations participated in the tournament, which was held at the Blau-Weiss Tennis Club in West Berlin from 6–11 June.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1967-federation-cup-tennis] United States defended their title, defeating Great Britain in the final.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1968-federation-cup-tennis] The **1968 Federation Cup** was the sixth edition of what is now known as the Fed Cup.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1968-federation-cup-tennis] 23 nations participated in the tournament, which was held at Stade Roland Garros in Paris, France, from 21–26 May.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/1968-federation-cup-tennis] Australia defeated the Netherlands in the final, in what was the first final not featuring United States, giving Australia their third title.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The **Billie Jean King Cup**, abbreviated as the **BJK Cup**, is the premier international team competition in women's tennis, launched as the **Federation Cup** in 1963 to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the International Tennis Federation (ITF).
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The name was changed to the **Fed Cup** in 1995, and changed again in September 2020 in honor of former World No.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The Billie Jean King Cup is the world's largest annual women's international team sports competition in terms of the number of nations that compete.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The men's equivalent of the Billie Jean King Cup is the Davis Cup.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The Czech Republic, Australia, Russia, Italy, and the United States are the only countries to have won both Cups in the same year.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] In 1919, Hazel Hotchkiss Wightman had an idea for a women's team tennis competition.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] This was not adopted but she persisted, presenting a trophy at the 1923 annual contest between the United States and Great Britain, named the Wightman Cup.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] Nell Hopman, wife of the legendary Australian Davis Cup Captain Harry Hopman, later took up Mrs Wightman's original idea.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] In 1962, a British resident of the United States, Mary Hardwick Hare, presented a dossier proving that support for such an event was overwhelming, persuading the ITF that it was a 'good idea' to have a team championship played over one week in a different venue each year.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] 40 years after Wightman's idea of a women's Davis Cup, it became a reality.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] In 1963, the ITF launched the Federation Cup to celebrate its 50th anniversary.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] Open to all nations the competition became a resounding success.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The inaugural event attracted 16 countries.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The competition was supported by the top players right from the start.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] Held at the Queen's Club, in London, the first contest was between Australia and the United States.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] Grand Slam champions Darlene Hard, Billie Jean King, Margaret Smith and Lesley Turner all proudly representing their country on court.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The United States would emerge the champion nation in the opening year.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] However, it was to be Australia in the early years, winning seven of the next eleven championships.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] Around 1980 the United States was able to establish some significant mark on the competition setting in future years a very high standard for others to compete against.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The first Federation Cup had attracted 16 entry teams, despite no prize money and teams having to meet their own expenses.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] When sponsorship became available, the number of teams expanded dramatically, first by the Colgate Group in 1976, and, from 1981 to 1994 by the Japanese communications and computer giant NEC.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] In 1994, there were 73 nations competing, with the host nation of a Federation Cup week was now being required to build a special tennis complex, giving rise to what became known as the Federation Cup "legacy".
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The additional costs of each event could be offset with the host nations viewing their involvement as providing an opportunity to boost their national game.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] For the 1992, a regional group qualifying format was introduced.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] In 1995, the event's name was shortened to the Fed Cup, and a new home-and-away format was adopted as per the Davis Cup, so that women could play for their country in their own country.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] There have been a number of smaller changes to the format since 1995.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The format change implemented in 2005 incorporates an eight Nation World Group I and eight nation World Group II both playing home-and-away over three weekends throughout the year.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] Three regional groups compete and there are promotions and relegations based on results.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The 2021 edition is set to have US$12 million in prize money.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] In April 2025, the sports betting platform 1xBet was named the *Official Global Betting Partner* of the event.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The deal includes exclusive branding rights across qualifiers, playoffs, and finals until 2026, marking the first standalone betting sponsorship of BJK's history.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] While many nations enter the BJK Cup each year, only 16 countries qualify for the elite World Group and World Group II each year (eight in World Group and eight in World Group II).
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] Once in the World Group or World Group II, four nations will be seeded in each.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The decision as to which nations will be seeded is made by the BJK Cup Committee, according to the ITF BJK Cup Nations Ranking.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] At the levels below the World Group and World Group II, the BJK Cup nations compete in Zonal Competition events, which are split into three zones: The Americas Zone, the Asia/Oceania Zone and the Europe/Africa Zone.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] In each zone there are two groups, Group I being the higher and Group II the lower, except for the Europe/Africa Zone, which also has a Group III.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] Within the Group zonal regions, teams are split into pools and play against each other in a round robin format.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The exact format of each Group event, and promotion and relegation between them, varies according to the number of participating teams.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] Two teams are always promoted from Europe/Africa Group I to that year's World Group II Play-Offs, while one team each go to the World Group II Play-Offs from Americas Group I and Asia/Oceania Zone Group I.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] This structure has been implemented since 2016.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] In World Group and World Group II, and World Group and World Group II Play-off ties, each tie is contested in a best of five matches format, and is played across two days.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] On the first day there are two singles matches, and then the reverse singles matches take place on the following day.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] In Zonal Groups I, II and III, ties are played over the best of three matches (two singles and a doubles).
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The First Round Ties in the World Group and World Group II are played on a home and away knock-out basis, and take place over a weekend in the early part of the year.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] World Group Semi-finals and Final are played over on a home and away knock-out basis, and take place over a weekend in July (Semi-finals) and September (Final).
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] Play-off ties for World Group and World Group II will also be played on a home and away knock-out basis taking place in July.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The choice of ground for First Round, Semi-finals and Play-off ties is decided by lot or goes automatically to one of the competing nations.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] As Groups I, II and III are played in a round robin format in all three zones, each event takes place at a single venue over one week.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] These are held in the first half of the year (to allow promotion of teams to the World Group II Play-off ties in the second half of the year), and dates and venues are decided by the BJK Cup Committee.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/billie-jean-king-cup] The Heart Award is the ITF's annual "MVP" award related to the Billie Jean King Cup, which "aims to recognise players who have represented their country with distinction, shown exceptional courage on court and demonstrated outstanding commitment to the team." The award was inaugurated in 2009.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The city's official name is a contraction of the (archaic) Dutch *des Hertogen bosch* ('the forest of the duke').
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The duke in question was Henry I, Duke of Brabant, whose family had owned a large estate at nearby Orthen for at least four centuries.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] He founded a new town located on some forested dunes in the middle of a marsh.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] At age 26, he granted 's-Hertogenbosch city rights and the corresponding trade privileges in 1185.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] This is the traditional date given by later chroniclers; the first mention in contemporaneous sources is 1196.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] His reason for founding the city was to protect his own interests against encroachment from Gelre and Holland; from its first days, he conceived of the city as a fortress.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It was destroyed in 1203 in a joint expedition of Gelre and Holland, but was soon rebuilt.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Some remnants of the original city walls remain.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In the late 14th century, a much larger wall was erected to protect the greatly expanded settled area.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Artificial waterways were dug to serve as a city moat, through which the rivers Dommel and Aa were diverted.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch became the birthplace and home of northern Renaissance painter Hieronymus Bosch.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Until 1520, the city flourished, becoming the second largest population centre in the territory of the present Netherlands, after Utrecht.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The city was also a center of music, and composers, such as Jheronimus Clibano, received their training at its churches.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Others held positions there: Matthaeus Pipelare was musical director at the Confraternity of Our Lady; and renowned Habsburg copyist and composer Pierre Alamire did much of his work at 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The wars of the Reformation changed the course of the city's history.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] During the Eighty Years' War, the city took the side of the Habsburg (Catholic) authorities and thwarted a Calvinist coup.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It was besieged several times by Prince Maurice of Orange, stadtholder of most of the Dutch Republic, who wanted to bring 's-Hertogenbosch under the rule of the rebel United Provinces.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The city was successfully defended against Prince Maurice in 1601 and again in 1603, but it eventually fell in the 1629 siege led by his brother Frederick Henry.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In the years of Truce, before the renewed fighting after 1618, the fortifications were greatly expanded.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The surrounding marshes made a siege of the conventional type impossible, and the fortress, deemed impregnable, was nicknamed *moerasdraak*, or the Swamp Dragon.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The town was nevertheless finally conquered by Frederik Hendrik of Orange in 1629 in a typically Dutch stratagem: he diverted the rivers Dommel and Aa, created a polder by constructing a forty-kilometre (25 mile) dyke and then pumped out the water by mills.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] After a siege of three months, the city had to surrender—an enormous blow to Habsburg geo-political strategy during the Thirty Years' War.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] This surrender cut the town off from the rest of the duchy and the area was treated by the Republic as an occupation zone without political liberties (see also Generality Lands).
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] After the Peace of Westphalia, the fortifications were again expanded.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In 1672, the Dutch *rampjaar*, the city held against the army of Louis XIV of France.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In 1794 French revolutionary troops under the command of Charles Pichegru attacked the city.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It was only weakly defended, and fell after a short siege.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Pichegru then crossed the rivers and put an end to the Dutch Republic.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Under the new Batavian Republic, established in 1795, both Catholics and *Brabanders* at last gained equal rights.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] From 1806, the city became part of the Kingdom of Holland and from 1810, it was incorporated into the First French Empire.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It was captured by the Prussians in 1814.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The next year, 1815, when the United Kingdom of the Netherlands was established, it became the capital of North Brabant.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Many newer and more modern fortresses were created in the vicinity of the city.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] A new canal was built, the 'Zuid-Willemsvaart', which gave the city an economic impulse.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Until 1878, it was forbidden to build outside the ramparts.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] That led to overcrowding and the highest infant mortality in the kingdom.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] At the end of the 19th century, the very conservative city government prevented industrial investment to avoid an increase in the number of workers and the establishment of educational institutions: students were regarded as disorderly.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] As a result, the relative importance of the city diminished.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] One of the few official Nazi concentration camp complexes in Western Europe outside Germany and Austria was named after 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It operated from January 1943, to September 1944 and was known to the Germans as Herzogenbusch (see List of subcamps of Herzogenbusch).
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] About 30,000 inmates were interned in the complex during this time, of whom about 12,000 were Jews.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In the Netherlands, this camp is known as 'Kamp Vught', because the concentration camp was actually located at a heath near Vught, a village a few kilometres south of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The city was occupied by German forces during World War II from 1940 to 1944.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The railway station was bombed by planes of the Royal Air Force on 16 September 1944.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The city was liberated between 24 and 27 October 1944 during Operation Pheasant by British soldiers of Major-General Robert Knox Ross's 53rd (Welsh) Infantry Division following the victory of the 1st Battalion, East Lancashire Regiment, of 158th Infantry Brigade over the enemy on 23–24 October.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] After the war, 's-Hertogenbosch was modernized, like many other cities in the Netherlands.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It was possible that it was only the geography that shielded the old town from rigorous reconstruction in those early years.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Just in time, the pendulum swung back to protecting the history of the city.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In 1956, the council wanted to demolish the Moriaan, the oldest brick building in the Netherlands, to give traffic better access to the market square.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The permit was refused by the government and instead the building was restored, starting in 1963.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Later, city councils became much more aware of the value of historic buildings and from about the turn of the millennium, the historic fortifications are also given much attention by the authorities.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The population centres in the municipality are: Bokhoven, Crevecoeur, Deuteren (former village), Dieskant, Empel, Engelen, Gewande, 's-Hertogenbosch, Hintham, Kruisstraat, Maliskamp, Meerwijk, Orthen (former village), Oud-Empel, and Rosmalen.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Climate in this area has mild differences between highs and lows, and there is adequate rainfall year-round.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Köppen Climate Classification subtype for this climate is "Cfb" (Marine West Coast Climate/Oceanic climate).
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The city of 's-Hertogenbosch has become a center of industry, education, administration and culture.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It is currently the fourth city of North Brabant.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It is home to many national and international businesses such as Heineken, Epic, Tyco International, SAP and many others.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Jeroen Bosch Hospital is the biggest employer in the area, with over 4,000 employees.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] There are also over 350 restaurants, pubs and cafés to be found in the city.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is also home to the European Ceramic Work Centre.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] This is a juried international ceramic residency where they invite artists, designers and architects from around to the world to explore the medium of Ceramics.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] This program was initially started in 1991 and continues to this day.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The city has its own food speciality, the Bossche Bol—effectively a giant profiterole, somewhat larger than a tennis ball, which is filled with whipped cream and coated with chocolate.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The spoken language is Maaslands (the variant spoken in 's-Hertogenbosch is called *Bosch* which is placed among the Central North Brabantian dialects, although other classification systems also describe it as East Brabantian), which is very similar to colloquial Dutch.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] De Toonzaal is a music venue for chamber music, improvised music, and experimental music.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] For popular music there is the venue W2 (or Willem II).
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Noordbrabants Museum is a provincial museum with an overview of works that Vincent van Gogh made in Brabant.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Design Museum Den Bosch is a modern art museum.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Jheronimus Bosch Art Center, is dedicated to the work of Hieronymus Bosch.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Other museums include the Swan Brothers' House and Museum Slager.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Also the National (Dutch) Carnavalsmuseum Oeteldonks gemintemuzejum is located in the city.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In the near future a new museum will be opened about the fortresses of the town and in general in Europe.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The house where the famous painter Hieronymus produced his paintings can be visited on the market square.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has a strong carnival tradition.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In its current form the story and symbolism dates from 1881 to 1883.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In these years some citizens created the legend of "Oeteldonk", whereby the city was renamed to Oeteldonk for the three day carnival.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] "Donk" is a reference to a dry place in the marsh.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The frog is widely used as a symbol during the 's-Hertogenbosch Carnival.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It is also a symbol of the Oeteldonk marsh.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It was also a remark aimed at Bishop Godschalk from Den Dungen, where 'Van den Oetelaar' was a common family name.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] He had wanted to forbid the traditional festivities of Shrove Tuesday that often led to excesses.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Oeteldonk is a village and therefore every inhabitant is a farmer or a '*durske*' (a girl or young woman), eliminating class differences.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The village is headed by the Mayor "Peer vaan den Muggenheuvel tot den Bobberd".
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Each year the mayor of 's-Hertogenbosch hands over his authority to the Mayor of Oeteldonk.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] On Sunday at 11:11 AM the Mayor of Oeteldonk then receives Prince Carnaval "Prince Amadeiro XXVI" at Oeteldonk central station.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] From there a parade of all carnival clubs escorts the company to the town hall.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The citizens of 's-Hertogenbosch wear traditional outfits throughout these days.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] A so-called *boerenkiel* is worn and every year patches are designed according to that years theme which can then be stitched onto the outfit.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The *boerenkiel* is often combined with a traditional farmers bandana and a long scarf in the colors of Oeteldonk.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The tradition of the Boerenkiel and / or Bandana is very different from the carnival traditions in the rest of the Netherlands.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Other aspects like the parade, the temporary name and the temporary flag (for Oeteldonk red, white and yellow) are very similar.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch was founded as a fortified city and that heritage can still be seen today.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] After World War II, plans were made to modernise the old city, by filling in the canals, removing or modifying some ramparts and redeveloping historic neighbourhoods.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Before these plans could come to effect, the central government declared the city a protected townscape.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Most historic elements have been preserved.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In contrast to cities like Rotterdam, 's-Hertogenbosch also survived the Second World War relatively unscathed.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Much of its historic heritage remains intact, and today there are always renovations going on in the city to preserve the many old buildings, fortifications, churches and statues for later generations.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The city center has a cosy atmosphere because of the almost continuous ramparts that still surround it.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It has been molded by the multiple rivers that convene on 's-Hertogenbosch, giving the center its strange street plan so different from the usual grid plan where streets meet at right angles.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The center is dominated by Saint John's Cathedral (*Sint-Janskathedraal* in Dutch), which dates from c.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] 1220 and is best known for its Brabantine Gothic design and the many sculptures of craftsmen that are sitting on almost every arc and rim along the outside of the cathedral.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In 2010 an extensive restoration was completed, undoing the damage of many years of wear-and-tear and acid rain.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] On the central square is the oldest remaining brick house of the Netherlands, 'de Moriaan', which was built at the beginning of the 13th century.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In the 1960s, de Moriaan was renovated to its former glory based on a famous 16th-century Dutch painting called 'De Lakenmarkt van 's-Hertogenbosch' ('The fabric market of 's-Hertogenbosch').
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The town hall is an original 14th-century Gothic building.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] After the town was conquered by the Dutch Republic in 1629, it received a new facade in the style of Dutch Baroque architecture.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It showcased the authority of the new masters, just like the new town hall in Maastricht would.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Hidden below the old city is a canal network called the Binnendieze, which once spanned 22 km (14 mi).
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It started out as a regular river, the Dommel, running through the city in medieval times.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Due to a lack of space in the city, people started building their houses and roads over the river.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Later, the Binnendieze functioned as a sewer and fell into disrepair.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In recent decades, the remaining sixth part of the old waterway system has been renovated, and it is possible to take several guided subterranean boat trips through it.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has an extensive and almost complete fifteenth-to-seventeenth-century city fortification.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It was made to profit from the city's strong defensive position, lying on a sandy hill in the center of a large swamp fed by many rivers.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] This also caused the main ramparts to be preserved, because they were crucial in keeping out the water.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In 2004 the city was awarded the title *European Fortress City of the year*.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In the years that followed it restored many of the city defenses to much of their old glory.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Apart from small sections of medieval walls, the main structure of the fortification is a late-medieval (fifteenth-century) wall.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The upper sections were removed when cannon became more powerful, and polygonal bastions were added, some after the conquest by the republic.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Most of these have not been restored to their original height, but do maintain their brick walls.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The citadel in the north west of the city does retain its original height.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Around the city itself many other fortresses can still be seen.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In the north east of the old city, the hexagonal gunpowder magazine, called *Kruithuis* is located close to the citadel.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It is one of only a handful that still exist in the Netherlands, and was built when the city was still part of the Spanish Netherlands.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It is planned to become the museum of fortress 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] One of the bastions of the fortress now houses the mini museum Bastionder.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It has been dug out in a bastion of the south side.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] On the inside it shows a unique wrought iron cannon, and an older bastion that was walled in by the current one.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] On the south side of the city, the city center and walls still border the Bossche Broek, an old polder that could never be made dry.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In 1995 the dyke of the Dommel broke and an enormous amount of water entered the polder.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It also flooded and blocked the main Dutch highway A2.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In order to prevent this in the future, the area was rearranged to store excess water in case of emergencies.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In 2006 the area had been furnished with higher dikes and locks that allowed a controlled flooding of the polder and some adjacent areas in case of emergency.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Bossche Broek is now a 22-hectare (54-acre) nature reserve, that stretches all the way to Vught.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It is connected to the Moerputten and Vlijmens Ven, with which it forms a Natura 2000 area.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Rare species in the area are the scarce large blue and the European weather loach.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Moerputten sports the Moerputten Bridge, a 600-metre (650 yard) long nineteenth century railway bridge and engineering feat.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] What is unique about the area is its close proximity to the city center.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The city is also the location of the *Bolwoningen* complex, an array of fifty experimental spherical houses designed by Dries Kreijkamp.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Lutheran Church, 's-Hertogenbosch is no longer used as a church.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The city has one professional football club, FC Den Bosch.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It is the 1967 successor of the professional branches of BVV (Bossche Voetbal Vereniging) and Wilhelmina.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Both of them still exist as amateur football clubs.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] As a successor of BVV FC Den Bosch can claim the national championship of 1948.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] This championship led to the construction of stadium De Vliert, which at one time had a capacity of 30,000.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Due to the less successful years that followed, the capacity is now only 8,500 visitors.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] FC Den Bosch was the first club of Dutch international player Ruud van Nistelrooy.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is more successful in field hockey.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The women's team in particular is a dominant force in the Dutch field hockey competition.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The professional basketball club Heroes Den Bosch is also very successful.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The city's rugby club is called The Dukes and dates from 1974.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It is located at a very scenic location at the foot of the city walls.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Because of the limited space, the club plays on artificial turf and part of the accommodation is subterranean.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It became the national rugby champion in 2008.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] As regards events the city is host to the Rosmalen Grass Court Championships, a combined ATP Tour and WTA Tour grass court tennis event played two weeks before the Wimbledon Championships.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The World Archery Championships and World Para Archery Championship were held here in June 2019.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] During these combined World Championships two separate venues were used: the Parade and the rugby fields of The Dukes.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] All finals took place in the arena at the Parade.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Parade is a historic square surrounded by high trees, situated at the foot of the nearly seven-hundred-year-old Saint John's Cathedral in the attractive center of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Zuid-Willemsvaart runs from the Meuse just north of the city towards Maastricht via Helmond and Weert.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In 's-Hertogenbosch it runs through the city proper, south east from where a bastion has been cut off from the citadel.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Because of this route it was impossible to widen it further than for ships of CEMT class II.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Therefore, the Máxima Canal of 8 km (5 miles) was dug just east of the city, creating a shortcut from the canal to the Meuse suitable for ships of CEMT class IV.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] On the remaining part of the Zuid-Willemsvaart west of the city is the industrial harbor of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is situated on the busy A2 motorway, the most important north–south connection of the Netherlands.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] This connection was established with the opening of the Dieze Bridge in 1942.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] From 1961 the Utrecht-'s-Hertogenbosch section was 2 times 2 lanes.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In 1970 the A2 was rerouted to the east of the city.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In 1989 it finally became a controlled-access highway.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In 1996 the section between 's-Hertogenbosch and Eindhoven became a controlled-access highway.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The situation in Maastricht was only solved in 2016, when the Koning Willem-Alexandertunnel was opened.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] On the east–west axis 's-Hertogenbosch is on the A59 motorway.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The A65 motorway between 's-Hertogenbosch and Tilburg is a regional highway, but is not completely access-controlled.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch railway station is on the Utrecht–Boxtel part of the railway stretch between Amsterdam and the Dutch industrial/tech center near Eindhoven.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] As a consequence north–south trains depart every ten minutes.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] On the Tilburg–Nijmegen railway trains run on a more modest schedule.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch railway station is also a major station for Arriva buslines that serve the city and most of its suburbs.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Other stations within the limits of the municipality are 's-Hertogenbosch Oost railway station and Rosmalen railway station.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Vught railway station is actually closer to the city center than that in Rosmalen.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has attempted to adapt to the growing popularity of the bicycle in Dutch cities.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] A reasonable amount of bike paths has so far been constructed in the town.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In 2011, the city was chosen as *Fietsstad 2011*—the top bike city of the Netherlands for 2011.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] This is a big achievement for a city where bicycle use is lower than in the rest of the Netherlands".
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has multiple vocational universities called *Hogeschool* in Dutch.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The HAS Hogeschool of about 3,500 students is focused on agricultural and food technology.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Avans Hogeschool is located in 's-Hertogenbosch and two nearby cities.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Joost is an art academy that is now part of Avans and dates back to 1812.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Fontys Hogeschool also offers some education in the city.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Jheronimus Academy of Data Science (JADS), located at the Mariënburg Campus in the center of 's-Hertogenbosch, and provides a number of data science programs at graduate (MSc) and post-graduate level (PhD).
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It is a department of the Eindhoven University of Technology and Tilburg University.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] In secondary education the City Gymnasium is a gymnasium (school) that originated from the Latin school of the city.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It is comparable to a grammar school and can trace its origin back 1274.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The same type of education and all other types of secondary education are offered by a number of large institutes.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Roman Catholicism is the dominant religion in 's-Hertogenbosch, with somewhat more than 40% of the population counting themselves as belonging to it.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Even so, attendance at mass is significantly lower than 40%.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Three churches in the city center are still in use by the Catholic church: Saint John's Cathedral, Saint Catherine and the Monastery Church of the Franciscans nearby the railway station.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] Smaller churches in use by the Roman Catholic church are: Saint Anne's Church in Hintham, Saint Landoline Church in Empel, Saint Willibrord Church in Maaspoort, Saint Lambert Church (Rosmalen), etc.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Protestant religion has seen its share of believers in the city fall from 20% to about 4%.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Eastern Orthodox Church is a new church in town.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] It is based at Saint Catherine's Church where Catholic worship services have been held again since 2021.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Arrahma Mosque has been built by the Moroccan community.
[src:billie-jean-king-cup/s-hertogenbosch] The Turkish community has the Orhan Gazi Mosque.
